<paper id="1514211561"><title>An Interleaving Model for Real-Time Systems</title><year>1992</year><authors><author org="University of Edinburgh," id="2367735380">Liang Chen</author></authors><n_citation>43</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>3820865</reference><reference>103974107</reference><reference>187509663</reference><reference>201148214</reference><reference>1491196069</reference><reference>1503973138</reference><reference>1602114053</reference><reference>2001748564</reference><reference>2072500626</reference><reference>2081092823</reference><reference>2113722134</reference><reference>2914494468</reference><reference>2915015834</reference></references><venue id="1150208541" type="C">Foundations of Computer Science</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0023865</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.52714">Integer</keyword><keyword weight="0.52136">Time domain</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Logic program</keyword><keyword weight="0.46066">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.51888">Rational number</keyword><keyword weight="0.53189">Natural number</keyword><keyword weight="0.424">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.54629">Decidability</keyword><keyword weight="0.57737">Bisimulation</keyword><keyword weight="0.48049">Interleaving</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>In this paper, we present a timed calculus, Timed CCS, which is an extension of Milneru0027s CCS with time. We allow time to be discrete, such as the integers or the natural numbers, or dense, such as the rationals or the reals. We extend the notion of strong bisimulation to timed processes and show that the largest strong bisimulation is decidable. The decidability is independent of the choice of the time domain.</abstract></paper>